AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED AND THE SPILL (12" RADIUS PUDDLE) WAS CLEANED UP, THEN ALL MATERIALS WERE CONSOLIDATED AND TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 PLASTIC 1-GAL JUGS WAS LOOSE BY A COUPLE OF ROTATIONS, CAUSING APPROX. 3 QUARTS OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH, OUT OF THE CARTON AND ON TO THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF A CORRUGATED QUAD DIVIDER AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT 55 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).

Hepaco personnel arrived on site and estimated to 30-40 gallons of diesel fuel released to a 50ft x 5ft area of asphalt and concrete only. column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: On 03/07/2021 at 1350 hours EST CSXT personnel in the Mobile, AL reported a derailment of 3 tank  cars.  While conducting re-railing operations, and performing inspections of derailed tank cars.   UTLX939654, a residue Methyl Mercaptan tank car was discovered to have an opened tattle tell  valve on the Pressure Relief Device.  This was discovered using air monitoring equipment that  detected H2S inside of the protective housing.  The valve was closed and the release was stopped.  ChemTrec was notified and CSX requested a call back from the shipper.  No state or federal  notifications required because release was less than the reportable required quantities.  Release  was limited to less than 1 gallon.  Cythnia Llames with Evonik Corporation (251-443-4000) was  notified. Specialized Professional Services Inc (SPSI), a CSXT response contractor, found the leak  and closed the valve to stop the release.       Theodore, Al-03/07/2021-UTLX930654-Methyl Mercaptan

column168: On 03/13/21 at 1046hrs personnel with CSX Intermodal Fairburn GA Terminal discovered JBHU283630, a loaded container of various NonHaz and Class 8 HazMat commodities, including 2 totes of UN3266, Corrosive Liquid Basic NOS(sodium hydroxide), 8, II; in 3000lb plastic totes w/aluminum cage. Material leaked less than 1gal of clear liquid onto asphalt. The container was isolated and GA EPD(report#96030) was notified,  The shipper, BNSF and JB HUNT representative was notified by CSXI Customer Service. JB HUNT emergency response contractor, HULLS Environmental, was dispatched to the scene and found one 3000lbs plastic tote released clear liquid of product due to valve not completely tighten and aluminum seal between the cap and cam fitting missing.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel secured the leak by tightening valve, and cleaned up the release site.  All lading, including generated disposal waste, was loaded back into the original freight container with proper load/block/brace and released to the shipper.  This incident did not require a special switching move. This incident did not require a Form 7.1..

column168: 2021-03-02  FRA Hazardous Material Inspector noted liquid coming from the top of tank car NATX 50587 (L / Ethanol Solution, UN1170) during his inspection activities at the CN Glenn Yard, Chicago, IL. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting security seals intact and noting liquid coming from the manway cover. One Manway bolt washer was found to be under the manway cover preventing a proper seal. The manway swing bolt washer was moved back to its correct position and manway lid secured for transportation. Shipper to apply for an OTMA for continued transportation.

US Ecology found one of six manway securement bolts less than tool tight contributing to a small release. The manway gasket was also replaced with a new gasket and the stain was cleaned with degreaser.

column168: On 03/03/2021, at 2328 hours, personnel in the CSXT Grafton Yard discovered CBTX 787477, a loaded tank car of Liquified Petroleum Gas, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the National Response Center, West Virginia DEP, and Shipper were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2021-0303-00376). Specialized Professional Services, Inc, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor line valve partially open and the secondary closure plug less than tool tight, resulting in a vapor release of hazardous materials. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Mark Mundy of NGL Supply, p[hone 519-312-7622. Contractor personnel closed the valve, installed the plug to tool tight. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 136  NARRI: 100

column168: On 3/22/2021, At 1448 ET, Elena Tonkova with LogiFlex contacted ERTS regarding a release of UN 3082, Santicizer 160 from an unknown amount of 230 kg blue poly drums impacting the trailer floor of trailer number 5372 and the concrete below the trailer located at 302 Quivira Dr, Laredo, TX 78045. Logiflex retained ERTS to coordinate the response, reporting and cleanup of the release. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor (HazMat Special Services). On3/22/2021, at 1806 ET, HazMat Special Services personnel arrived on site and reported that Laredo FD was on site and had containment in place. HazMat Special Services personnel reported that a reported hard braking incident resulted in a load shift causing 1 drum to develop a stress crack and 1 drum to be punctured by a load strap. HazMat Special Services personnel estimated a total of 70-gallons of "UN 3082, Santicizer 160" released in all, 20-gallons of which released to the concrete under the trailer. HMSS personnel utilized granular absorbents to clean the impacted areas. The damaged drums were over packed. All waste generated was taken off site for pending disposal.

column168: On March 7 at 06:12, while enroute to Fayetteville, NC the driver ran off the road and the tractor tires sunk into the mud on the left shoulder of SB I-95 pulling the tractor into the guardrail. The impact of the guardrail caused the tractor and trailer to roll over into the median. Prior to impact the vehicle was traveling at 65 MPH in a 70 MPH zone. The transport unit was the only vehicle involved. The trailer shell was punctured at Compartments #1 and #3 as a result of the rolling over the steel guardrail/posts. First responders constructed dikes and placed sorbent booms in the median ditch and prevented any gasoline from entering storm drains. No surface water was impacted. The leak was relatively slow and pump-over to another tanker was safely conducted within about 6 hours of the crash.
column169: Reinforce to all drivers, especially new/younger petroleum transport drivers the importance of staying aware of personal limits of fatigue and the importance of maintaining mental alertness in all phases of the work cycle. This is especially true in the early morning hours at daybreak. Regardless of time-of-day, there can be no compromise of personal safety and the safety of others in the course of commercial transportation and handling of hazardous materials.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Indianapolis, IN-03/23/2021- PROX 252980-Waste Environmentally Hazardous Substance, Liquid N.O.S.  On 03/23/2021, at 1135 hrs., the FRA in the CSXT Hawthorne Yard discovered PROX 252980, a loaded tank car of Waste Environmentally Hazardous Substance, Liquid N.O.S., leaking from pressure relief device. The car was isolated and (GFL Environmental, IDEM, and NRC) were notified. Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the pressure relief device had actuated and product on top of the car. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Jason Henkel 204-781-2600. Contractor personnel took a pressure reading on the car which was 0 psig and snoop tested the pressure relief device but could not find a leak source and decontaminated the car or cleaned up spilled material. The leak could not be duplicated was secured and the car was released for transport pending an OTMA1 approval. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 will be required.   Cause Code: 422 NARRI: 2

column168: On 03-23-21 Gary Kearny FRA Haz-Mat inspector was inspecting a cut of cars when he found WCHX 30061 leaking from the bottom outlet valve. He contacted me about 1030 to tell me that it is not a major leak, but a drip and the car was the seventh car from the Locomotive. He also stated it was an 1170 Haz-Mat. Flammable Liquid. Gary contacted Lori Zeka in Customer Service to get the waybill and told us the car was going to Meiers Winery in Blue Ash.  Scott Wentz and I left the shop to the location of the car when I called Brian Myers, John Keffer and the Car Shop(James Daley and Kash Helton). Scott and I looked at the ERG to find out what liquid we are now dealing with. The liquid was ethanol.  I instructed James and Kash to get their spill tub and Blue Flags and come to the train at the Swimming Pool(MP C11.3 Oasis Sub).  Scott and I met Gary Kearny at the leaking tank car and gave a quick inspection and found the car was dripping once every 10 seconds and had duct tape along the bottom outlet valve for some unknown reason.  After the Car Shop Blue Flagged the train, James and I went under the car to find the valve was leaking at the handle. We tried moving the handle to see if we could close the valve any tighter, but shipping seal 103622 would not allow us to do so.  I asked Gary if we could move the car 3 to 4 miles to the customer to have it unloaded. Gary called Joel Roberts with the FRA and Joel said that the first step is to try and stop the leak by a Certified Tank Car Company and only then would “Washington” allow for a OTM and that move would not allow it to the customer, but to our yard.  At 1130 I called Eric Drumm with Drumm Inc. who are a local tank car company to help with this situation and while talking to them, I found at tag on the valve that showed this valve was last rebuilt by Drumm Inc themselves on 02/2018. Eric said he would have guys there by 1400. In the meantime, Rob Payne contacted the FRA to apply for the OTM to have the car moved to the yard.  Drumm Inc. arrived at 1415. We gave them a job briefing, gave them masks and headed to the car.  Terry and his assistant with Drumm Inc. inspected the valved and started to tighten the flange that holds the teflon valve packing material. Drumm Inc. was not able to stop the leak but slow it down due to the teflon packing material worn out. They were able to reduce the drip from 1 every 10 seconds to 1 drip every 60 seconds. I asked how long the valve was good for, and they said depending on frequency of use, 3 to 5 years. This valve is a little over 3 years old. While inspecting the car, they also found the safety cap gasket was not the correct size. Unable to remove the cap fully to replace the gasket due to shipping seal 103621 applied, the seal was removed, the gasket replaced and a seal from the FRA applied. This was the reasoning for the tape.  Rob contacted FRA in Washington and we were given permission and the OTM as long as the leak did not drip on any public crossings. Dr

column168: RECEIVED CALL FROM CONTROL THAT A SMOKING BOX WAS DISCOVERED IN TRAILER 277. ARRIVED AT TRAILER, UNSURE WHICH BOX WAS NOT SMOKING, SUPERVISOR IDENTIFIED WHICH BOX, WAS NOT SMOKING AT THAT TIME. CAREFULLY SHIFTED BOX, STARTED SMOKING FROM SPACE IN BOX FLAP ONCE BOX WAS SLIGHTLY FLEXED. IMMEDIATELY LEFT AREA, CONTACTED BASE/PE WHICH ARRIVED AND OPENED BOX TO REVEAL A LOT OF SMOKE AND FOUR LARGE MULTI-ITEM BOXES OF MATCHES. ONE APPEARED TO HAVE BURNED FROM WITHIN DUE TO SELF-IGNITION. EXTERNAL SHIPPING BOX WAS NOT DECLARED AS HAZMAT. INTERNAL BOXES DID CONTAIN UN1944 MARKINGS AS WELL AS FLAMMABLE SOLID LABELING.

column168: On 3/23/2021, Gary Kearny (FRA Haz-Mat Inspector) was inspecting a cut of cars when he found car# WCHX30061 leaking from the bottom outlet valve.  Gary contacted mechanical supervisor Nicholas Longshore at 1030hrs to state such, telling Nick that it was not a major leak, but a drip (every 10 seconds).  Car was 7th back from locomotive. Gary stated it was UN1170 Haz-Mat flammable liquid / Ethanol.  Crew responded with spill tub and blue flags.  Nick and Scott Wentz, AVP Mechanical, met Gary at leaking car and after quick inspection found duct tape long the bottom outlet valve.  Upon further inspection found valve was leaking at handle.  Tried moving handle to close the valve tighter, but shipping seal 103622 prevented this.  Nick asked Gary if car could be moved 3-4 miles to the customer for unloading.  Gary called Joel Roberts (FRA) who stated first step is to try and stop the leak by Certified Tank Car Company, and only then would "Washington" allow for a OTM and that move would only be to our yard - not customer.  1130hrs contacted Eric Drumm (Drumm Inc.) local tank car company for assistance. In conversation, it was found the tag on valve showed last rebuilt date of 2/2018 was by Drumm Inc themselves.  Eric dispatched his crew to site for 1400hrs arrival.  Meantime, Rob Payne, contacted FRA to apply for OTM to have car moved to yard.  1415hrs Drumm arrived, inspected valve and tried to tighten.  Due to teflon packing worn out, could not stop leak but slowed to a drip (every 60 seconds).  Valve is over 3yrs old with a life expectancy 3-5 years, depending on use. Drumm also found the safety cap gasket was not the correct size.  Tried to remove to replace gasket, but couldn't due to shipping seal 103622 applied.  Seal was removed, gasket replaced, and a seal from the FRA was applied.  This was the reasoning for the duct tape.  Rob contacted FRA in Washington and IORY and OTM were given permission as long as the leak did not drop on any public crossings.  Drumm taped a spill pad in the opening and around shaft. Car moved to MCYD to Track 09. Spill pads left there and placed tub under car.  Arrangements being made to transload car.
column169: Suggest shipper to closely inspect cars for any defects and educate employees on risks and hazards.  Take 5 and have a briefing with employees to not overlook all the working mechanics of a valve and to take the time to make sure products in tank cars are transported safely, which in effect could save lives and the environment.
column172: Railroad tank car

column168: On March 18, 2021, at 0800 hours, CSX ACCA Yard personnel discovered that while conducting switching operation the Y39317 derailed two cars.  As a result, UTLX 201932, residue last contained Cyclohexanone Solutions, was de-trucked on the A end causing the tank head to strike the coupler of a box car in the same track.  This coupler strike caused a breach of the tank’s A end head, resulting in a release of product vapor.  CSX personnel responded, contained the vapor release by plugging the breach, re-railed the two derailed cars, and subsequently cleaned/purged the damaged tank car.  The damaged car is currently being held at CSX’s ACCA yard awaiting settlement from car owner.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: Our driver loaded sulfuric acid at FMI Miami. When he closed the dome lid his dome-lid gasket became pinched or crushed near the hinge of the dome lid. He performed two leak checks but did not realize a small amount of acid was leaking from the pinch point. He exited property and stopped at a set of railroad tracks. The stopping of the vehicle caused the liquid to surge where the first small amount of acid was released on the roadway (US-60). The driver then drove towards his destination. I was informed that a vehicle owned by our company had left FMI property possibly leaking acid. I called the driver and had him pull over immediately to perform a leak check. He confirmed that a small amount of acid had leaked onto the ground where he came to a stop. He put a 5 gallon bucket under the drain hose to catch any additional drips. The only know release of sulfuric acid occurred at the RR tracks in Miami, AZ where the vehicle made a complete stop and also where the vehicle ultimately stopped on US-60 near MM-219. This was confirmed by our clean up response crew and by AZ DPS who drove the entire route.  Once the driver confirmed that his tanker was not sealed properly I contacted AZ DPS Duty Office, AZDOT HAZMAT and the NRC.
column169: Drivers are trained to check their dome lid gaskets before closing their dome lids to make sure the gasket is seated properly. Once the dome lid is closed, drivers are required to inspect the edge of the dome lid with gloved hand to make sure the gasket has not become pinched or twisted before tightening wing nuts. Drivers can be informed of this incident to illustrate the importance of performing the checks they required to do every time a product is loaded.

column168: Driver was flagged down while driving and once stopped, informed of a leak from the trailer. The driver got out and noticed product dripping out of the drain tubes from the crash box. The individual that flagged him down stopped all traffic until the fire department and police arrived approximately 10 minutes later and cleaned the spill. Art, our driver, climbed up to the crash box and found a washout cap had come off of the nipple but was still contained within the crash box. Art then replaced the cap onto the washout nipple and was able to continue the short distance to the consignee.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s  location to the intended waste management facility. During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the  purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued  transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered that approximately 5 gallons of  material had escaped from a small crack that had developed in the container.  Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to  decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into the salvage drum.  Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued  transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or cracking was  observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is  loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural  integrity. IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect  all containers used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required specifications.

column168: On 03/23/2021, SNLU 196885 was reported leaking upon deramp at the San Bernardino, Ca IMF. This unit was listed as carrying hazardous materials.  In the interest of safety, the unit was placed on hold and placed in the containment pit pending inspection.  United Pumping was hired to remediate the load. Interior inspection revealed a mixed load of freight, 2 layers high with multiple straps and a bullboard  for securement. The origin of the leak was a 5 gallon pale of Supreme Seal Solvent   Based Concrete & Paver Sealer. A nail from the pallet was able to  puncture the pale and allow about 3 gallons to leak out with less that one gallon reaching the ground. The Solvent was deemed hazardous (UN1263) by  United Pumping. Unit has been remediated and released for outgate.

column168: 2021/03/16 - Frost on the exterior of the protective housing of tank car GATX 66210 (L / UN1003 / Dimethyl Ether, Class 2.1) was noted while performing an inventory of rail cars staged on a CN industry spur track in Morris, IL. All appropriate departments notified. CN's response team responded noting security seals intact. The protective housing security seal was removed and the lid opened for inspection. The inspection revealed that liquid was leaking from the sample port valve causing the frosting. The valve handle was found to be not fully closed and it's securement plug to be less than tool tight allowing product to escape. The valve was properly closed and the securement plug tightened by the CN response team.

column168: At approximately 08:33 on 3/4/21, the GATX 214238 was observed to potentially be leaking from the protective housing.  The area around the car was isolated in all directions and responders were notified.  The Yakima FD responded along with contract and BNSF Hazmat responders.  The liquid line valve was found partially open along with the closure plug being cross threaded and not tool tight.  The valve was closed, the plug inspected with thread sealant applied and secured in the valve body.  All released propane quickly dissapated.  The car was then allowed to continue in transportation.  Volume loss estimates are based upon observations from responders at the incident.

column168: On 3/13/2021 there was a small leak from a 55 gallon metal drum at the Veolia, Newington, CT office. It was on a truck in the parking lot at the office. Employees saw the leak when they returned from jobs for that Saturday. When employees walked by the parked truck, the employees noticed a solvent smell. They inspected the truck and found a a small leak under the vehicle. Employees opened the back door of the truck and inspected all containers within the truck. Upon inspection it was determined that there was a small crease in a metal drum on the bottom of the container. The drum was placed in an 851A2 salvage drum to continue transportation to the ultimate disposal facility.     The drum leaked less than 1 pint of mixed solvents while in transit due to the crease. The liquid was cleaned up with spill pads and absorbent and the drum was over-packed into an appropriate 85 gallon salvage drum along with the clean up materials. The duration of release is anticipated to be a small drip from the drum for about 12 hours with no more than a quart leaking.   On 3/13/2021 the Veolia safety manager of Marlborough,MA was notified. The results of the investigation is that a drum had a small  crack in it due to human error when loading the container with a drum cart.  The container was inspected prior to shipping and did not have any issues. It appears that the leak was caused when the container was moved with a drum cart and the cart creased the metal drum and leaked overnight. The shipper was notified of the leak. It is unsure if the container was moved by a Veolia employee or the customer employee.
column169: The cause of a spill was a crease in a 55 gallon drum while loading it and preparing it for transportation. Veolia employees must continue to inspect drums when handling prior to and during transportation and notify management upon discovery of a leaking container. Veolia will continue to review the causes of spills with employees the best method to over-pack a leaking container or to prevent any further leaking of containers. In this particular case, the container was inspected and looked as if it was OK to transport as offered. During the investigation, it was discovered that the container was damaged when being loaded into the truck. The shipper employees and Veolia employees helped with loading the drums. This was reported to the customer/shipper and more care will be used in the future to prevent a similar issue from happening again.

column168: On 3/23/2021,  Logiflex ERTS requesting assistance with a UN3082 release from unit #5372. The trailer is fully loaded and an unknown amount has released at this time. At 1551 ET, Logiflex retained ERTS to coordinate response and remedial operations. ERTS dispatched E3 (environmental contractor) to respond, secure and clean the release. E3 personnel arrived on site and advised that appeared that two pallets (four drums on pallet) had shifted towards the nose of trailer; noted only one strap at the rear of the trailer; advised that there were two released material impacts on the asphalt surface outside of trailer: 1) near the rear of trailer measuring 4-ft wide x 20-ft in length; and 2) nose of the trailer, 3-ft wide x 10-ft in length. E3 personnel  identified one poly drum with puncture apparently from a nail from pallet; contractor inspected all drums during removal; puncture in drum was located at edge of bottom and side; as previously reported during initial assessment by contractor, the punctured drum was located on one of the pallets that shifted most likely during transit; estimated amount of material released is 30-gallons. E3 personnel confirmed all response/cleanup activities have been completed; all remaining drums/pallets reloaded to nose of trailer and straps added to pallets; E3 generated two, 55-gallon poly drums of solid waste (granular absorbents, PPE), and one, 95-gallon overpack poly drum containing the leaking 55-gallon punctured drum and contents (approximately 20-gallons); waste to be transported offsite to contactor facility pending profiling and disposal;

column168: At approximately 3:20 pm an unloader at door noticed that a package started smoking and shortly after began to flame. The unloader reported the fire to his supervisor and the supervisor notified maintenance.  A maintenance mechanic extinguished the package fire.  Later the package was brought over to the hazmat processing area where the package was operated and inspected by the facility first responder.  The contents of the package were two sealed lead acid batteries and the terminals were not protecting One battery terminal was sticking outside of the package and was charred and the second battery had no visible damage.  It was also identified that the package was not declared as containing sealed lead acid batteries. The terminal on the lead acid battery that was protruding outside of the package made contact with metal equipment and generated a spark / arcing causing the package to ignite.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the next customer location.  Upon arrival at customer location, driver was performing his  load check and identified a cracked container.  The crack resulted in a release of approximately 5  gallons.   Driver proceeded to place the compromised container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition,  all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and  placed onto the trailer  for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was  observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity.  IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required specifications.

column168: Our driver just started unloading and had the pump running on low while verifying nothing was leaking.  When he turned up the pump speed to normal delivery flow one of his hoses blew near the end collar.  3-5 gallons hit the ground covering an area of 4 feet by 10 feet.  The customer handled clean up.  The hose was within its required inspection range (Schneider requirement of one year).  After inspecting we found that the lining was gouged inside which is usually a good indicator when it is close to the end that a tankwash ran a pressure washer wand inside and damaged it.
column169: We unfortunately don't know which tankwash specifically caused this because not all hoses are used on every delivery so there is no telling when and where that one was cleaned.  That said our tankwash director has a weekly call with all the tankwashes in our network.  This was revisited with all of them.  He has also since put together a slide show presentation outlining a few hose related spills we had due to damaged lining in recent months (the others were all non-hazardous releases) to help reinforce the point.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: Driver was transferring diesel fuel from an underground storage tank and resulted in approximately a  25 gallon spill.  Product splashed on a concrete pad and then flowed down a narrow path in the store's parking lot into a private road located on the Walmart property. A portion of the diesel went into the storm sewer on the road.   Shield Engineering managed the cleanup efforts for Eagle.  Tennessee Emergency Management Agency (TEMA): Report #429 National Response Center (NRC): Report #1300486 & 1300542 ***Please note the first NCR included incorrect info regarding the road. The second number was provided when called back to correct the road being on private property.   Cones were set up to protect the area, spill paid and speedi dri were put down, and the storm sewer catch  basin was vacuumed.
column169: The investigation determined that the customer's veedor root was not calibrated correctly. This provided incorrect numbers regarding how many gallons were actually in the tank.

column168: Driver Thomas Roberts, operator of tractor#102, trailer#127 was returning from a delivery and pick up at McRoberts BEA- Fill Station, Enon Valley Pa, 16120. While traveling eastbound on I-80 near mile marker 44 in Allegheny Twp, Butler County, Pa, when he lost control of the vehicle exiting the highway to the north, then crossing highway to the south, overturning traveling excess of 300' before coming to rest on south side of highway straddling the driving lane and berm. The onboard CNG tanks were not compromised and there was no gas release. Fire/EMS, recovery vehicles, and State Police waited until company representatives could arrive on-site and advise how best to handle the vehicle and it's contents.
column169: The reason(s) that Thomas Roberts lost control of his vehicle are still unclear. The gas module functioned as designed and did not fail. Recommendations to drivers going forward is to wear seatbelts, avoid distractions while driving, and adjust speed for the road conditions, not just the posted speed limit.

column168: Driver was driving a semi tractor pulling a tank trailer heading southbound on HWY 34. The driver crossed the white line, over corrected and then lost control of the tractor/trailer .  The tractor/trailer overturned coming to rest on the passenger side on the side of the road just before the Roosevelt overpass.  Emergency personnel were notified immediately after the incident. The tank trailer was breached due to the impact of the rollover.  The fire department diked the area.  contained the spill and transferred to drums.  Enviromark was dispatched to the scene to manage the scene and oversee the cleanup.
column169: After accident investigation, review of video and speed reports, It was determined the driver was speeding 5 mph over the speed limit and failed to negotiate a curve , over -correcting at the last minute and flipping the tractor/ trailer on the passenger side.  The path of the truck and the drivers reaction time would indicate that the driver was distracted.  The driver was issued a citation for failure to maintain control.  It was daylight and raining heavily. ne Company initiatives going forward : Working closely with our insurance company, Great West Casualty, on accident mitigation, implementing new orientation policies and procedures and utilizing the telematics tools for hard brake, speed and hard curve events that have recently become available to us through our ELD provider, Keep Truckin, We will also be putting together a Journey Management Plan for these routes focusing on hazards and dangers en route.  There is a company -wide push on speeding and distracted driving prevention through one-on one intervention, flyers and video training the driver tablets.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ERTS was notified by Tanya Rogers with A & R Logistics (First Choice Logistics) regarding an unknown amount product (UN1593) release that occurred at a customer location. The initial cause is currently unknown. No drains or waterways are reported to have been impacted by the release. ERTS dispatched and environmental contractor to investigate, secure and remediate the release. The site contact, Jim Fowler, advised that when they began to offload the product they noticed the tanker leaking at the center valve. They believe that the gasket between the valve and the tank is leaking and allowing product to release near the valve. Approximately 5-gallons has been released underneath the tank and is forming a large puddle. Environmental Works stated that they have located the release. The stated that the facility personnel had cleaned some of the released material with oil dri. Some of the product did impact a puddle in the containment pit. It has been raining since the spill occurred and they estimated that the puddle now contains 1000-1500 gallons of impacted water. Environmental Works is currently utilizing the vacuum truck to collect the impacted water. Environmental Works stated that Chemisphere personnel tested the impacted water in their onsite lab. They stated that the tests came back within limits for their water permit and will be able to dispose of the water down the drain in the containment pit. Environmental Works will offload the impacted water from the vac truck back into the site containment pit.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: During routine delivery of sulfuric acid to the PacifiCorp Naughton Power Plant, the delivery driver connected to a delivery line that was out of service and tagged out and proceeded to unload product. The product flowed to a tank that was undergoing maintenance and was released through open valves. Plant personnel in the vicinity smelled the acid and alerted the driver to stop the delivery. The sulfuric acid traveled into a concrete-lined industrial wastewater trench where it mixed with other wastewater streams from the plant and was neutralized. No acid left containment or was spilled on soil. Duration of the release was less than 10 minutes The company shipping the product- Groendyke Transport failed to follow contractual operations and procedures at the Naughton Plant. 1.- When the driver arrived, he hooked up to a camlock fitting that was tagged out. -Loading and unloading of materials- Plant staff needs to be present. Tagged out(Do Not Use) 2.- He proceeded to off-load the Sulfuric Acid by himself with no plant staff. -Loading and unloading of materials- Plant staff needs to be present.

column168: Package was received at our shipping dock from a customer with a cockpit voice/data recorder(CVR) inside the package. The 90 day beacon on the CVR contains 1.75g lithium metal content so this was a lithium metal battery packaged in equipment shipment. Package had no markings that it was a dangerous goods/hazardous materials shipment. Our shipping department personnel unpackaged the unit and delivered the unit to our repair department. We notified the shipper they shipped a dangerous good without the proper labels and documentation and that they needed to remedy this in the future and that Universal Avionics was required to report the incident. There was no release.
column169: Our personnel have received training on recognizing hazardous materials arriving at our dock with issues and to notify management when an incident occurs. We provided additional training to recognize when a hazardous material arrives without the appropriate markings or documentation and no release and to immediately report it to management so we can capture all the appropriate information in order to report the incident. We have also notified customers and dealers through newsletters, a notice on our customer website and a service bulletin about reshipping this particular product for repairs and the need to ship as dangerous goods/hazardous material.

The ramp was directed by Dangerous Goods Administration to have FedEx Spill Cleanup staff contain the shipment in a salvage drum and hold it pending further disposition instruction.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: Passenger side front steer tire blew out at highway speed, forcing driver into guiderail/bridge. At the end of the guiderail/bridge is a downhill embankment. Truck/trailer rolled onto its passenger side down embankment. Load of 18 industrial batteries weighing approximately 2000# each, were loaded in accordance with Federal, State and local regulations. They were loaded to prevent forward, aft and side to side movement. When truck rolled onto its side, the load made contact with the metal roof of the trailer, tearing the metal roof open. Most of the load was contained within the trailer. A couple of batteries did slide just outside the trailer and released about 20 gallons of battery electrolyte onto the ground surface. No Diesel or other truck fluids occurred. 911 and Hazmat recovery were called immediately, to stabilize and mitigate the situation. Hazmat recovery and emergency services up righted the truck and trailer. The load was also up righted. Leaking acid was contained and load was secured onto another unit, to be transported from the scene. The site was remediated to clean up the battery acid per the state requirements. The batteries were cleaned up and re-palatized for transport back to East Penn Manufacturing Co., Lyon Station PA for disposal/recycle of the batteries.
column169: Truck had a passenger side steer tire blowout. Driver was travelling road speed, with no adverse road or weather conditions when tire failed. Vehicle was serviced on 2/19/2021 at 330,989 miles. At that time all tires were checked for air pressure,tread depth, wear patterns and any visible damage/defects. This tire did not raise any safety concerns at that service interval. At the time of the accident the truck had 339,059 miles. Next maintenance was scheduled for 345,989 miles (every 15,000 miles). column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: During routine delivery of sulfuric acid to the PacifiCorp Naughton Power Plant, the delivery driver connected to a delivery line that was out of service and tagged out and proceeded to unload product. The product flowed to a tank that was undergoing maintenance and was released through open valves. Plant personnel in the vicinity smelled the acid and alerted the driver to stop the delivery. The sulfuric acid traveled into a concrete-lined industrial wastewater trench where it mixed with other wastewater streams from the plant and was neutralized. No acid left containment or was spilled on soil. Duration of the release was less than 10 minutes The company shipping the product- Groendyke Transport failed to follow contractual operations and procedures at the Naughton Plant. 1.- When the driver arrived, he hooked up to a camlock fitting that was tagged out. -Loading and unloading of materials- Plant staff needs to be present. Tagged out(Do Not Use) 2.- He proceeded to off-load the Sulfuric Acid by himself with no plant staff. -Loading and unloading of materials- Plant staff needs to be present.
column169: When Tankers arrive at security, plant personnel will meet them, and escort them onto the property to oversee the entire delivery process.

column168: Three individual shipments that were each being transported in a plastic jerrican overpacked in a fibreboard box were observed leaking during PM sort operations at the FedEx Express hub in Memphis, TN. All three shipments were offered by DuPont Electronics Polymers in Dayton, OH and were traveling to the same recipient, EIDCA Specialty Products Company in Kingston, ON Canada. The shipments were nearly identical, with each overpacked jerrican containing PHS Polymers in Methanol. The commodity is classified as UN1230, Methanol, Class 3 with a Division 6.1 subsidiary hazard, packaging group II. The package associated with tracking number 170547141688 was declared with a net quantity of,17 L, while the package associated with tracking number 170547141703 was declared with a net'quantity of 16.1 L, and the package associated with tracking number 170547141714 was declared with a net quantity of 16.9 L. Further investigation showed in each case the inner jerricans were leaking from their closures into the outer fibreboard overpack packaging of each shipment. The shipments had been offered as dangerous goods, and Shippers Declarations for Dangerous Goods were offered with the shipments. Both the inner jerricans and the outer fibreboard overpack boxes had UN specification markings on them. The·involved packages were placed in salvage drums pending receipt of amended Shippers Declarations for Dangerous Goods from the shipper.

column168: ON MARCH 8, 2021 A TRADEBE TRANSPORTATION LLC DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CUSTOMER'S (ENPRO) LOCATION TO LOAD THIS MATERIAL AT THEIR LOADING DOCK AND CONTAINMENT AREA. THE LOADING PROCESS CONSISTS OF THE FOLLOWING : THE CUSTOMER'S (ENPRO) PERSONNEL STAGES THE TOTS AND DRUMS AND USING  ENPRO EQUIPMENT PUMPS THE MATERIAL INTO OUR BULK TANKER: THIS PROCESS TAKES BETWEEN 2 AND 2.5 HRS TO LOAD.  THE TRADEBE DRIVER HEARD A LOUD NOISE AT APPROXIMATELY 1H AND 45 MIN INTO THE LOADING PROCESS AND NOTICED THE ENPRO TRANSFER PUMP LEAKING THE TRADEBE DRIVER INSTRUCTED THE ENPRO PERSONNEL TO S PERSONNEL ADVISED THE TRADEBE STOP PUMPING . THE ENPRO PERSONNEL ADVISED THE TRADEBE DRIVER TO DISCONNECT HIS HOSES AND LET THE MATERIAL SPILL INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE TRADEBE DRIVER ASKED THE ENPRO PERSONNEL IF  THE MATERIAL COULD BE RETURNED TO THE TOTES BUT THEY SAID NO. THE TRADEBE DRIVER WATCHED THE ENPRO PERSONNEL WHO WOULD BE CLEANING UP THE MATERIAL AND WAS TOLD THAT IT WOULD BE ENPRO PERSONNEL.  THE ENPRO PERSONNEL INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO PULL HIS VEHICLE OUT OF THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  WE BELIEVE THAT ALLOWING THE TRUCK TO MOVE OUTSIDE THE CONTAINMENT AREA CONTRIBUTED TO THE CONDITIONS TAHT LED TO THE RELEASE OF MATERIAL NEAR OR INTO THE CATCH BASIN BY CAUSING THE LEAKED MATERIAL TO TRAIL THE TRUCK AS IT PULLED AWAY.
column169: TRADEBE HAS DONE AN INTERNAL INVESTIGATION INTERVIEWING A NUMBER OF DRIVER'S THAT HAVE BEEN TO THIS LOCATION TO SERVICE THIS CUSTOMER AS WELL AS CORRESPONDING WITH ENPRO TO REVIEW LOADING AND SAFETY PROCEDURES.

The package, associated with tracking number 784926502735, had no dangerous good markings or labels, and no Shippers Declaration for Dangerous Goods was offered. There was labeling on the outside of the package indicating the shipment was a gift, and the Commercial Invoice document associated with the package specified the contents as crafts and candy. The package was seized by US Customs officials prior to disposition to the consignee to search for illegal substances. The package was subsequently returned to the FedEx Express destination station in Kentwood, MI after it had been opened and examined by Customs. The outer packaging was dampened by a small amount of liquid when it was returned and had several markings and seals indicating it had been inspected. Staff at the destination station were informed that several plastic bottles in the box contained liquid that was analyzed by Customs, and the liquid was determined to be nearly pure alcohol, perhaps being sent as moonshine. There were other items in the package that were not dangerous goods as well. Some of the inner containers also had tape on them with printing indicating that Customs had opened and inspected them, indicating they had been modified from the original condition they had been shipped in. After receiving the package, FedEx Spill Cleanup staff at the destination station were directed by Dangerous Goods Administration to contain the shipment in a salvage drum and hold it pending further disposition instruction.

column168: Package was received at our shipping dock from a customer with a cockpit voice/data recorder(CVR) inside the package. Package had proper markings that it was a UN3091 dangerous goods/hazardous materials shipment. Our shipping department personnel unpackaged the unit and found that the paperwork showed UN 3090 and was missing the shippers declaration. We have not notified the shipper that they shipped a dangerous good without the proper documentation as we do not know where the error actually occurred. There was no release.
column169: Our personnel have received training on recognizing hazardous materials arriving at our dock with issues and to notify management when an incident occurs.
